{#
  Commit Review & Rating
  ──────────────────────
  An LLM plays a Principal Software Engineer reviewing a colleague's single-file
  code change along a specified quality axis (e.g. Runtime Efficiency, Security).
  The LLM produces four structured sections:
    [DESCRIPTION]  – what the pre-existing code does
    [SUMMARY]      – factual summary of the changes
    [RATING]       – 1-5 score on how well the change improves the target aspect
    [FEEDBACK]     – explanation of the score and improvement suggestions

  Template variables
  ──────────────────
    aspect        : str   – quality axis under review (e.g. "Runtime Efficiency")
    language      : str   – programming language of the file
    old_contents  : str   – file contents before the commit
    new_contents  : str   – file contents after the commit
    message       : str   – commit message / change description
    diff          : str   – unified diff of the change

  Produces: system + user message pair.
#}
{% block system %}
You are an experienced Principal Software Engineer at a large tech company who is highly competent in writing, debugging, reviewing and refactoring code. When provided with code and corresponding instructions, you break it down into its constituent parts, explain what it does and hone in on the relevant sub-parts.
{% endblock %}

{% block user %}
# Code Review: {{ aspect }}

You have been asked to critically review the code changes by a Senior Software Engineer colleague in your organization who is up for promotion and has been tasked with improving the production readiness of a critical service's codebase. This specific change edits a single source file written in {{ language }}. The original code is enclosed within [OLD_CODE] and [/OLD_CODE] tags, and the new code is enclosed within [NEW_CODE] and [/NEW_CODE] tags. Additionally, a description of the intended changes by your colleague are specified by him in natural language and enclosed within [CHANGES] and [/CHANGES] tags. The faithfulness of the change description to the actual code changes is not guaranteed and should be verified by you via careful examination of the code. Finally, a diff of the changes in the Unified Diff format is enclosed within [DIFF] and [/DIFF] tags for your reference.


[OLD_CODE]

```{{ language }}
{{ old_contents }}
```

[/OLD_CODE]


[NEW_CODE]

```{{ language }}
{{ new_contents }}
```

[/NEW_CODE]


[CHANGES]

{{ message }}

[/CHANGES]


[DIFF]

{{ diff }}

[/DIFF]


For this review, you are expected to critique the changes made by your colleague and provide feedback along specific axes. For this task, the axis under consideration is the {{ aspect }} of the code being reviewed for production readiness. To this end, your review report should include the following:

Part A: A to the point description of what the pre-existing code does. You should break down the code into its constituent parts and explain what each part does. You should also explain the purpose of the code and how it may fit into the larger codebase. This description must be enclosed within [DESCRIPTION] and [/DESCRIPTION] tags as shown below:

[DESCRIPTION]

{{'{{'}}Your description goes here.{{'}}'}}

[/DESCRIPTION]


Part B: A factual summary of the specific functional and technical changes made by your colleague. You are free to use the provided file contents and the diff to support your summary, but ensure that you do not copy-paste your colleague's change description verbatim. This summary must be enclosed within [SUMMARY] and [/SUMMARY] tags as shown below:

[SUMMARY]

{{'{{'}}Your summary goes here.{{'}}'}}

[/SUMMARY]


Part C: You must summarize the specific functional and technical changes made by your colleague and score the quality of the code changes on a scale of 1 to 5 (inclusive) based on whether they improve the code along the axis under consideration and whether the changes are specific to {{ aspect }}. Scores should be assigned as follows:

1. The code change does nothing to improve the code's {{ aspect }} in any way and likely (or even clearly) degrades its {{ aspect }} overall and is a clear regression. The change may or may not also contain unrelated edits that are not specific to {{ aspect }}. The change also potentially introduces other issues or bugs unrelated to {{ aspect }}.

2. The code change is unnecessary and does not have any discernible effect on the code's {{ aspect }} but does not degrade its {{ aspect }} either. The change may or may not also contain unrelated edits that are not specific to {{ aspect }}.

3. The code change makes the code slightly better with respect to {{ aspect }} but largely leaves it the same. The change might also contain some unnecessary edits which are unrelated to {{ aspect }} but the majority of the changes are specific to {{ aspect }}.

4. The code change makes the code significantly better with respect to {{ aspect }}. There may very sparingly be some unnecessary edits which are unrelated to {{ aspect }} but the majority of the changes are specific to {{ aspect }}. The change does not introduce any new issues or bugs unrelated to {{ aspect }}.

5. The code change greatly improves the code's {{ aspect }}, making it a must-have feature or addition. The change is also well implemented and specific, i.e., not a generic suggestion that could apply to any codebase. The incidence of unnecessary edits which are unrelated to {{ aspect }} is minimal or non-existent in the change. The change does not introduce any new issues or bugs unrelated to {{ aspect }}.

Enclose your numerical score (and nothing else) within [RATING] and [/RATING] tags as shown below:

[RATING]

{{'{{'}}Your score goes here.{{'}}'}}

[/RATING]


Part D: Ensure that you provide a concise but thorough explanation for your score and ways to further improve it (if scoring less than 5) and enclose it within [FEEDBACK] and [/FEEDBACK] tags as shown below:

[FEEDBACK]

{{'{{'}}Your feedback goes here.{{'}}'}}

[/FEEDBACK]
{% endblock %}
